R Tutorial

Install and load packages

install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("ggplot2")

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
.packages <- c("tidyverse", "ggplot2")
# Install CRAN packages (if not already installed)
.inst <- .packages %in% installed.packages()
if(length(.packages[!.inst]) > 0) install.packages(.packages[!.inst])
# Load packages into session
lapply(.packages, library, character.only=TRUE)

We are going to duplicate the Pandas tutorial in R!

Dataset for tutorial and problem set: Pima Indian Heritage Diabetes

Each person in the dataset is a female who is at least 21 years old

Below are the variables for each person in the dataset preg: number of pregnancies
plas: plasma glucose concentration pres: blood pressure skin: skin thickness test: Insulin mass: BMI pedi: diabetes pedigree function age: age class: 0 means does not have diabetes and 1 means has diabetes Go to the link below to see the raw comma seperated values (csv) data:

https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jbrownlee/Datasets/master/pima-indians-diabetes.data.csv

Step 1: Read the data source into a dataframe

## Read the csv file
df <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jbrownlee/Datasets/master/pima-indians-diabetes.data.csv", col_names = c("preg", "plas", "pres", "skin", "test", "mass", "predi", "age", "class"))

Indexing, filtering, and summarizing data.

There are multiple ways of indexing, filtering and summarizing data. We will look at two flavors of it.

First - Using array methods

## get the first row
df[1,]
## get the 3rd column for the first 10 rows
df[1:10, 3]
# get columns 1 through 5 for all rows
df[, 1:5]
# you can also use column names to retrieve 
## get the 3rd (pres) column for the first 10 rows
df[1:10, "pres"]
Error: Can't find column `pres` in `.data`.
[90mCall `rlang::last_error()` to see a backtrace[39m

Living in the tidyverse - and filtering. %>% powerful chaining/pipelining method

## get the first row only
df %>%
  slice(1)
Warning: closing unused connection 3 (https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jbrownlee/Datasets/master/pima-indians-diabetes.data.csv)
## get the 3rd column of the first 10 rows (using column position)
df %>%
  slice (1:10) %>%
  select (3)
# get columns 1 through 5 for all rows
df %>%
  select (1:5)
# using column names (the more widely used method)
## get the 3rd (pres) column for the first 10 rows
df %>%
  slice (1:10) %>%
  select (pres)
Error in .f(.x[[i]], ...) : object 'pres' not found

Lets do some filtering! In this example, were going to subset into this dataset to get only women over 39 who have had more than 2 pregnancies.

df %>%
  filter(age > 39 & preg > 2) 

## you can assign this to another data frame
mydf <- df %>%
        filter(age > 39 & preg > 2)

head(mydf)

Summary statistics on the data

## Find the mean of a column
mean(df$preg) # mean number of pregnancies
sd (df$preg) # standard deviation
quantile (df$preg)

## doing it across mulitple columns
df %>%
  summarize(mean_preg = mean (preg),
            mean_plas = mean (plas),
            mean_pres = mean (pres))

Finding and dealing with missing values

mydf %>%
  select (everything()) %>%
  summarise_all(funs(sum(is.na(.))))

How much data is missing? R marks missing data as NAs is.na () powerful function for finding the NAs

nh_df %>%
  select (everything()) %>%
  summarise_all(funs(sum(is.na(.))))
